<br>
1) Mitigation AC is completely broken at the high end of the game. I can't speak to this with any authority, but if Monks can be preferred tanks due to their mitigation working as well as a plate class, AND they have better avoidance skills, that is completely hosed and needs to be fixed. NOW.<br>
<br>
2) Warriors have trouble getting groups at the high end of the game, because they cannot generate aggro fast enough to make them useful tanks in that most highly sought after situation, a &quot;max efficient xp group.&quot; This is one issue that I think needs to be addressed.<br>
<br>
3) Warriors of all levels are unhappy because they think the warrior class should always be the clear choice as a tank. Under any circumstances, they think a warrior should be picked over a Paladin or SK.<br>
<br>
To address 1) several good ideas have been suggested. The best of which is a &quot;defensive table&quot; or a mitigation fudge factor. This would multiply the damage done to non-plate classes by a certain amount, or divide the damage done to plate classes by a certain amount. There are a bunch of different opinions about whether the groups should be made by class (Heavy plate=warrior, SK, Paladin, Light plate=Cleric, Bard, etc) or by armor type (plate classes, chain classes, leather classes, etc). Myself, I think any implementation of this idea would require a LOT of tweaking, so I'm not particular about what particular form of it gets rolled out initially.<br>
There's also the idea to adjust hp recieved on All/All items for class, where Warriors would get 100%, SK/Paladins 90%, etc. This seems like an okay idea to me too, as long as it's not applied to mana as well. The Hard Cap on mana affecting all classes, it seems to me that +mana items that are all/all should give the full benefit to all the listed classes.<br>
EDIT:  The more I think about it, the more appropriate I think it would be to limit +mana items this way, despite my objections.<br>
<br>
To address point 2), I think perhaps Verant should consider lowering the Taunt refresh timer from levels 53 onward, by about half a second each level. At 53, taunt refresh would drop to 5.5. At 56, it would drop to 4 seconds. At 60, any class with the Taunt ability would be able to taunt every 2 seconds. Yeah, this would apply to paladins and SK's too, but what the hell? It would only really help the warriors, and hopefully it wouldnt' be too overpowered. If so, the timer could just be adjusted again. (wonder if evade is tied to the taunt skill, only works in reverse?)<br>
<br>
To address 3), the idea that warriors should ALWAYS be the number one choice for tanking anything, anywhere.  I think this idea is completely messed up, and I have no patience for those warriors that make this claim. <br>
<br>
I recognize that if a paladin chooses to go the Templar route over the Crusader route (read: focusses on improving healing and mana, rather than offensive/defensive attributes) with his AAXP, then he becomes a very viable xp group healer, but that does not mean that at any point in the game, paladins should return to being the tank outcasts they were after Kunark. And being always second (or third) choice as a tank would relegate <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  non-AAXP</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> enabled paladins back to that point, despite the other abilities we might have, in my opinion. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=268670" target="new"><img src="http://www.emeraldis.com/~booraembj/smallbah.jpg" align=left> </a> <br> <br> <br><center><font face="coronet, comic sans ms" font size="6" font color="191970"><span style='filter:glow(color=#87ceeb,strength=3);width:100%'> Aragir Lancot</span> </font><BR>
<BR><font size="1">"One man plus the truth equals a majority."<BR>
Cerivel tells you, 'Hehe grats on scaring off a level 56 giant that hits for 360'<BR><BR>
